<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,573,1269]" box="[151,886,573,597]" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,573,597]" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Description.</emphasis>
Male. Body length 
<quantity box="[502,580,573,597]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="107" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
, primary colour dark brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,573,1269]" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Head. Posterior portion dark brown, rest yellowish brown and whitish dusted, antennae including scape and pedicel yellow to yellowish red, arista bare, black and basally thickened. Vibrissal callus distinct, with 3-4 vibrissae together with 3-5 very short bristles, palpi yellow and slightly enlarged. Genae and lower part of head ‘bearded’ with long and very fine hairs.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,573,1269]" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Thorax. Acrostichal bristles indistinct, two pairs of scutellar bristles of equal size, katepisternum bare, other chaetotaxy standard, wings darkened, all veins dark.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,573,1269]" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">
Abdomen. Sternite 3 rectangular, slightly broadened caudally with small projection, sternite 4 more or less square with distinct incision proximally, both without distinct bristles. Sternite 5 with short lobes arcuately curved inwards, with dense very short bristles medially (
<figureCitation box="[1048,1112,893,917]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1497,1516]" captionTargetBox="[153,1051,209,1447]" captionTargetId="figure-14@5.[149,1053,209,1453]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 7-11. 7: Amaurosoma bernasconii sp. nov., female, allotype, abdominal sternites 4 to 7. 8-9: Microprosopa ozerovi sp. nov., male, paratype; 10-11: Norellisoma vonickai sp. nov., female. 8 – abdominal sternites 3 to 5; 9 – praegonite; 10 – abdominal sternites 5 to 7; 11 – abdominal sternite 8. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (Figs. 8, 10); 0.1 mm (Figs. 7, 9, 11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468113" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468113/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), praegonite straight, broad and acutely pointed, beak-shaped, without bristles (
<figureCitation box="[980,1046,925,949]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="5.[113,152,1497,1516]" captionTargetBox="[153,1051,209,1447]" captionTargetId="figure-14@5.[149,1053,209,1453]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs. 7-11. 7: Amaurosoma bernasconii sp. nov., female, allotype, abdominal sternites 4 to 7. 8-9: Microprosopa ozerovi sp. nov., male, paratype; 10-11: Norellisoma vonickai sp. nov., female. 8 – abdominal sternites 3 to 5; 9 – praegonite; 10 – abdominal sternites 5 to 7; 11 – abdominal sternite 8. Scale bars: 0.5 mm (Figs. 8, 10); 0.1 mm (Figs. 7, 9, 11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468113" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468113/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1127,573,1269]" box="[181,373,957,981]" pageId="4" pageNumber="107">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
